  footnotes: []
english:
  title: Epitaph for Zhao Yushu's Tomb
  author: Kim Il-son
  language: eng
  text: |-
    Alas, more than a year has passed since Yushu departed this world, and my sorrow deepens. Yet it is not Yushu himself I mourn—it is his learning that moves me to tears. His learning was not the learning of the civil service examinations, which the world refuses to believe in, yet I alone have faith in it. Because my faith runs deep, so too does my sorrow, and many others share in this grief.

    Yushu possessed a luminous and uncluttered mind, a respectful bearing, and humble speech. He concealed his learning rather than displaying it—truly the finest among my circle of friends. Yet his natural gifts were extraordinary; he wished to leap in a single bound to profound heights, without first establishing the foundation of disciplined practice. This was the flaw of his brilliance. I once pointed out this deficiency to him, and he rose in sincere apology, showing himself to be one who did not resist correction.

    Yushu's family name was Zhao, his personal name Guanglin. His great-grandfather Quan served the Taizong with distinction and was enfeoffed as Duke of Hanchuan, from which his descendants inherited hereditary privilege. His father Hun served as magistrate of Kumsan, and his mother, Lady Yi, conceived him after dreaming of the sun. This was in the year Guiwei. From childhood his nature was keen and penetrating; in manhood he became composed, devoted himself to the learning of Lixi, and would sit upright alone in his study with quotations from the sages affixed to all four walls to remind himself. Though his family was poor, he remained untroubled. His grandparents lived on, and with four elders in one household, he brought joy to every heart. He had two younger brothers, Guangfu and Guangzuo, with whom he daily studied the Great Learning, striving to guide them toward goodness. In all his pursuits he surpassed others, yet in gatherings he moved harmoniously without distinction, earning the respect and affection of all.

    He passed the examination for advanced scholar in Bingwu with me, and later obtained his doctorate in Renzi, receiving appointment as Corrector in the Chancellery and serving finally as Functionary of the Court of Imperial Sacrifices. His friends provided the coffin and performed the rites, and after a month had passed, he was buried on the hills of Goyang in Gyeonggi Province, on the fifteenth day of the fifth month in the year Jiaxin. Yushu married Lady Liu but had no children. His father, upon learning this, lamented to Heaven, "My son never sinned against Heaven—why is Heaven so cruel?" Soon after, he too departed.

    His friends, grieving all the more deeply, gathered together and pooled their resources. Following the example of Xu Shizi of old, they erected a stone monument at the tomb. All entreated me to inscribe it with these words.

    Alas, shall I compose an epitaph for Yushu? If I do not, he will be forgotten. Therefore I write:

    Born in distant seas, even after a thousand years more,
    he could not meet the Sage.
    Born in Guiwei, died in Jiaxin—
    thirty-two years, the span of Yan Hui's life.
    O stone monument at the grave's head,
    how can you grant him the gift of not fading away?
  footnotes:
  - key: ''
    value: Yan Hui (顔淵, 521-481 BCE) was Confucius's most virtuous disciple, known for his profound wisdom and moral character. He died young at thirty-two, the same age as Yushu. The comparison suggests both his tragic early death and his spiritual excellence.
  - key: ''
    value: The reference to Xu Shizi (徐孺子) alludes to a famous figure from the Eastern Han known for his virtue and humility. The practice of erecting a stone monument at the tomb following his example was an honorable tribute reserved for persons of exceptional character.
  - key: ''
    value: The 'learning of Lixi' (濂洛之學) refers to the Neo-Confucian philosophy of the Lixi School, emphasizing moral cultivation and spiritual discipline rather than practical examination preparation.
  - key: ''
    value: The 'civil service examinations' (科擧) were the primary path to official advancement in East Asia. That Yushu pursued a deeper moral philosophy rather than mere examination success was unusual and marks his distinction.
